metadata.name: Acrylic #224
metadata.description:
A deep dive into particles is what led me to acrylic. Bright and deep colours with smooth lines while all connected in the journey to the target. 
My main inspiration was the smooth movement of a flock to a endpoint and where a particle should go if not one but multiple points present itself. Make sure you take a look at the live view to see every detail of the piece.

metadata.name: Wild Palms #130
metadata.description:
When I was a child walking with my father in the park, he once told me if I could hear the trees talking to each other. I listened, and in the noise of the leaves and seeds in the wind, I truly recognized their languages and voices. I was so overwhelmed by the depth and diversity of the world and the creatures that inhabit it, that it is still one of my most vivid memories. 

When I walk through parks or forests, I always listen to what they say. It is unlikely that I will ever be able to engage in their dialogue, but it is always like a touch of the magical immensity of life.

Wild Palms is the name of a gallery of our friends with whom it is always a pleasure to talk in the language of humans, and they have a garden right in the gallery.
In the project we mix childhood memories and friendship, the aesthetics of woodcuts, Polaroid and hand-printed photos with echoes of the digital voice of our present.

Thanks to YulikolaY for getting the code ready for production.

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

January, 2023

metadata.name: Mistakes #3
metadata.description:
Have you ever found your path by accidentally making a mistake?
This was what happened to me... while exploring some possibilities in coding I made a mistake, and that made me explore on that direction and creating this project!

"Mistakes" project represents how chaotic our lives can be and how many decisions we need to make in our path. All the choices are possible. All the choices are valid. But still we need to decide where to go.

Don't ever be afraid to try and make mistakes. They can bring you to such wonderful places!

metadata.name: The Artifact #185
metadata.description:
An archaeological artifact from the future, when many everyday objects are produced by generative algorithms. Some artifacts are in one piece, and others are fragmented. The color palettes are named after the rivers where artifacts in this design have first been discovered.

URL and interactive features:

- Append &r=<number> to the URL to change the image resolution. For example, &r=0.5 will halve the pixel count along both width and height, and &r=2 will double it.

- Append &d=<number> to the URL to change the pixel density. For example, &d=0.3 will generate a very quick, coarse render, and &d=2 will generate very fine stippling.

- Append &p to the URL to reveal detailed parameter settings used for the artwork.

- Append &h to the URL to suppress the notification that rendering is in progress.

- Press 's' in the live view to save the rendered image as a png.

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript. Polygon boundaries are determined via t-SNE, which is implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used. Licensed CC0.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Automatic #449
metadata.description:
Cellular automata is fascinating :) Applications ranging from physics and biology to modeling and architecture, with artistic and aesthetic representation always following along. Perfect example for emergence, how simple even byte-size rules result in complex structures, forming patterns and unpredictable behaviors...

This one is simple, 1d elementary cellular automata and the 256 rules as the foundation, where each iteration consists of the following elements: base rules - 3 are selected and allocated into the start row compositions, a set of shapes is assigned to a grid of various sizes. Occasionally, dynamic rule set is added - where a rule is randomly transformed into another random rule on a random row of the grid. A vertical or horizontal alignment of the grid is chosen an a color set assigned. Sometimes, a simple 2d noise is applied to lighten (or well, darken) things a bit. The grid is finite and confined by the amount of cells in a row and amount of rows fitting the canvas given cell size.

The properties are recorded as features, more as a reference to the building blocks, rather then rarity indication. Probably be best viewed in live mode :)

Pressing 's' in live mode will save the png of the output.

metadata.name: 8x8 Pixel Creatures #102
metadata.description:
Pixel art is a highly relevant art form, which rarely gets the kudos it deserves from the wider art world. 

I wanted to include some small pixel art creations in another project I was working on. However, I got a bit carried away, and ended up creating a pixel creature generator.

I came to like these little pixel creatures, so I decided to share them, and give them a life on FxHash - I hope you like them too. 

There are a bunch of variations, and a reasonable chance one or two styles may never be minted, so mint away, and I hope you get a rare one. Also, minters get a share in future royalties of their mints, which may be cool in any reality where they become popular one day.

I'll probably reference these guys on other relevant art I produce, when it seems appropriate.

Coded in p5js.

metadata.name: This is the lie  #831
metadata.description:
The Project of the Nameless Sheep stems from an artistic and provocative necessity that aims to conceptually unite the Orwellian philosophy of 1984 with the thoughts of the great master Modigliani. The latter once stated, "I shall paint your eyes only when I know your soul."

The collection is a cry of disagreement towards destructive and uncontrollable globalization. It draws inspiration from an impersonal observation of modern society, critically examining historical events, corporations, and notable figures who have sold their soul for individualistic power that disregards the lives of others and the environment.

An ever-evolving project that will mature its search for soulless bodies over time.

1984 token, at a price as provocative as the theme of the collection.

Any reference to individuals, things or concepts is entirely coincidental and generated by a hash.
